{  
  "response_text": "The destock total trajectories, tracked across simulation runs and behavioral configurations, begin near zero and exhibit a gradual but accelerating increase over time. All lines follow a roughly linear ascent until approximately step 50, after which the rate of destockation slows, with the lines exhibiting increased divergence in their slopes. Some trajectories, notably the gray and red lines, persistently exceed intermediate values of 100 households, reaching 140+ households at the final timestep. The intermediate blue and dark blue lines align closely around 120 households, while the purple and green lines culminate near 100 households.   \\\n\nThe trajectory of the dark teal line diverges sharply from others, peaking at ~140 households before converging back to the mean trend. This suggests distinct decision-making dynamics under specific parameter configurations, though all agents adhere to the E-RO behavioral type with fixed risk aversion (risk-att-init = 0.5) and inactive social learning (social-susceptibility = 0). The flattening of trajectories post-step 50 coincides with climatic variability-induced vegetation stress, as rainfall fluctuations (rain-mean = 200, rain-std = 100) likely constrained sustainable stocking rates. Variance between runs grows noticeably beyond step 40, reflecting cumulative impacts of stochastic rainfall and household-level decision lag.   \\\n\nThe slow destockation rate for the lighter lines (below 100 households) implies resource conservation strategies emerged in those simulations, possibly due to higher intrinsic preferences overriding stocking decisions. These patterns align with E-RO agents’ inherent focus on personal consumption over collective resource management. Decision-makers using this model might interpret these trajectories as evidence that homogeneous risk-averse strategies in stable social networks struggle to adapt to climatic instability, necessitating either diversified behavioral types or adaptive safisficing thresholds to mitigate long-term biomass depletion."
}

